http://purl.org/dc/terms/description.value: In Grades K-8, students receive a strong foundation in economics. One-semester Economics for Grades 9-12 emphasizes economic decision making. Students will explore the interrelationships among consumers, producers, resources, and labor as well as the interrelationships between national and global economies. Additionally, students will examine the relationship between individual choices and the direct influence of these choices on occupational goals and future earning potential.
Economic Decision Making
Students will make decisions after considering the marginal costs and marginal benefits of alternatives.
Evaluate the roles of scarcity, incentives, trade-offs, and opportunity cost in decision making

http://purl.org/ASN/schema/core/comment.value: e.g., PACED decision making model, cost/benefit analysis

http://purl.org/dc/terms/description.value: Justify various economic solutions to problems affecting an individual or society using marginal costs and marginal benefit analysis
Exchange and Markets
Students will evaluate different allocation methods.
Identify various allocation methods used in different circumstances, countries, and economies
Demonstrate changes in supply and demand (e.g., shifts, shortages, surpluses, availability) that influence equilibrium price and quantity using a supply and demand model
Students will investigate the role of producers, consumers, and government in a market economy.
Analyze the role of consumers in a market economy
Compare and contrast major forms of business organizations

http://purl.org/ASN/schema/core/comment.value: e.g., sole proprietorships, partnerships, corporations, non-profits, franchises

http://purl.org/dc/terms/description.value: Evaluate intended and unintended consequences of government policies created to improve market outcomes
Students will evaluate the degree of competition among buyers and among sellers in markets.
Compare and contrast various degrees of competition in markets

http://purl.org/ASN/schema/core/comment.value: e.g., perfect competition, monopolistic competition, oligopoly, monopoly

http://purl.org/dc/terms/description.value: Explain how differences in the extent of competition in various markets can affect price, quantity, and variety
National Economy
Students will analyze the current and future state of the economy using economic indicators.
Analyze economic indicators used to measure economic performance

http://purl.org/ASN/schema/core/comment.value: e.g., Gross Domestic Product, unemployment, Consumer Price Index [CPI]

http://purl.org/dc/terms/description.value: Evaluate the impact of advancements in technology, investments in capital goods, and investments in human capital on economic growth and standards of living
Students will analyze monetary and fiscal policies for a variety of economic conditions.
Compare and contrast the roles and functions of financial institutions in the United States
Examine monetary policy tools used by the Federal Reserve System

http://purl.org/ASN/schema/core/comment.value: e.g., open market operations, discount rate, reserve requirement, interest on reserves

http://purl.org/dc/terms/description.value: Examine fiscal policy tools used by the executive and legislative branches of the government
Determine the relationship between the national debt and the federal budget
Global Economy
Students will analyze ways in which trade leads to increased economic interdependence.
Analyze the role of comparative advantage in trade and global markets using available data and a variety of sources

Explain ways in which current trends in globalization affect economic growth, labor markets, rights of individuals, the environment, technological advancement, and resource and income distribution in different nations
Research the impact of international and national economic and political policies on global trade using a variety of sources from multiple perspectives
Personal Financial Management
Students will analyze factors affecting income, wealth, and financial risk.
Analyze the impact of education, training, and other factors on productivity and income potential

http://purl.org/ASN/schema/core/comment.value: e.g., interpersonal skills, workforce readiness skills, ethics

http://purl.org/dc/terms/description.value: Evaluate a variety of strategies for making personal financial goals to build short-term and long-term wealth
Analyze insurance as a risk management strategy to protect against financial loss

http://purl.org/ASN/schema/core/comment.value: e.g., auto, health, life, homeowners, renters, disability, liability

http://purl.org/dc/terms/description.value: Students will analyze the role of credit in personal finance.
Evaluate costs and benefits of using various types of credit

http://purl.org/ASN/schema/core/comment.value: e.g., interest rates, fees, penalties, rewards

http://purl.org/dc/terms/description.value: Analyze factors that affect credit worthiness
Evaluate various strategies to correct and avoid credit issues

http://purl.org/ASN/schema/core/comment.value: e.g., credit counseling, identity protection, debt consolidation, bankruptcy
